<table width="97%" border="0" align="center"><tr><td style="font-weight: bold; font-size: large;">Our name is Legion</td></tr><tr><td>By Stephanie Thompson</td></tr><tr><td style="font-size: xx-small;">March 22, 2001</td></tr><tr><td>Our name is Legion, and we are gamers.<br><br>And like many gamers, I aspire to be on the other side of the fence, helping to create games.<br>
<br>
Even knowing what I know about the inner workings of game companies. Surprisingly enough, they don't sit around in their underwear all day, eating pizza, telefragging their coworkers on the internal Quake server... well, unless that's what was behind those closed doors marked with police and biohazard tape.<br>
<br>
Oh, a girl can dream. But I digress.<br>
<br>
Who are the gaming programmers, designers, and artists? They're just like you or me - people who love games but are lucky and talented enough to be able to create them. Why do they do it? To give something back to an industry that's given them countless hours of enjoyment, blisters on their thumbs, and cramps in their necks. <br>
<br>
They certainly don’t do it for the job security. Knowing that you're only as good as the last game you shipped and all that matters are the games that ship, not the ones that get cancelled. <br>
<br>
The people calling the shots at gaming companies are not gamers, not programmers; they are suits, businessmen, financials, looking at the bottom line and not the finished product. They think in terms of competitors, release dates, how much the game costs them, how they can cut corners, how they can edge out others in the market. They decide when the game ships, if it ships, in what condition it ships, and the people who pour their lifeblood into creating the game have fuck-all to say about it.<br>
<br>
Every time I read public forums where people slam and curse the developers and creators of the game, I just want to grab them by the shoulders and give them a good shake.<br>
<br>
(Well, more than that, but we'll leave the senseless violence for later.) <br>
<br>
"Oh, you don't care, you can't program, I could do better, you just want a paycheck, you don't care about what you give to the fans, what about us, blah blah blah!"<br>
<br>
Know what? You just have no fucking idea. I know a good deal of people in the gaming industry, in many different aspects of the field. I've been there when the workday begins at 8 AM and ends, if it ever ends, around 3 or 4 AM the next morning. I don't know about you, but I sure as hell wouldn't spend a 12+-hour workday on something I didn't care about, at the cost of my personal life, my family, fuck the salary. And yes, salary means no overtime, for those playing along at home.<br>
<br>
I've watched people spend months, nay, years on a game, fine-tuning and tweaking all they could, tracking down bugs, fixing them, trying to tune specs, on and on and on to create something they believed in, could feel proud in being a part of, to put out there for other people to enjoy. And be months away from getting it just the way they wanted it, the way the fans wanted it, and have it yanked out from under them, because, <br>
<br>
"ohifwereleaseitnowwecangetallthemommiesanddaddiestobuyitforjuniorintheinsanebanalmadnessthatistheholidayseason."<br>
<br>
All for an extra buck and a holiday boost to sales.<br>
<br>
Not because the programmers wanted to.<br>
<br>
Not because the designers wanted to.<br>
<br>
Not because the artists wanted to.<br>
<br>
Because the higher-ups wanted to.<br>
<br>
Yes, ideally, games should be about the game experience. Vanquishing the foe, solving the puzzle, making right what was once wrong (So I watch Quantum Leap, sue me), teamwork, love, hate... Well, you know what I'm getting at. But once it moves beyond a couple of guys making a game in their garage and giving copies to their friends, it becomes a business, and when it becomes a business, it's all about the bottom line. Money. Sales. Profit. Not fun, not truth, justice, and the nobility of slaying the dragon and rescuing the villagers.<br>
<br>
And damn it people, for the most part, you're bright individuals. You know what big business is like. But when it comes to laying blame in the gaming industry, you're egging the wrong people. So before you start ranting somewhere at a programmer or designer because your client crashes or your frame rates are for shit or your machine locks up, think for a minute. Do you really want to alienate the people who are willing to help you? Put up with corporate bullshit to put out a game for you, the universal gamer? Gnash their teeth in frustration when their hands are effectively tied about if and when to release a game and in what condition?<br>
<br>
Do you?<br>
<br>
Aim your righteous indignation where it belongs.</td></tr></table><!-- banner2 code --></td>
	</tr>
